## 3. Revolutionary Platform-Isolated Bytecode

### Bytecode Format Version 3

TortureLang's binary bytecode format is currently at **version 3**, having undergone two previous revisions to eliminate any possibility of cross-format ambiguity.

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              TortureLang Bytecode             │
│  ┌─────────┬────────┬────────┬────────────┐  │
│  │ Magic   │ Version│Platform│ Endianness │  │
│  │ 4 bytes │ 2 bytes│ 2 bytes│  1 byte    │  │
│  ├─────────┴────────┴────────┴────────────┤  │
│  │         Environment Binding             │  │
│  │            SHA-256 Hash                 │  │
│  │             32 bytes                    │  │
│  ├─────────────────────────────────────────┤  │
│  │         Instruction Stream              │  │
│  │         (platform-specific)             │  │
│  └─────────────────────────────────────────┘  │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

Each platform gets its own:

- **Unique opcode mapping** — opcode 0x01 means different things on different platforms
- **Specialized execution engine** — compiled with the exact same compiler, flags, and system libraries
- **Environment binding hash** — prevents accidentally running code built with a different CMake configuration

### Cross-Platform Security

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Build Environment Binding Calculation       │
│                                              │
│  Inputs:                                     │
│    ├─ Source directory path                  │
│    ├─ Binary directory path                  │
│    ├─ Compiler path & ID                    │
│    ├─ Compiler version                      │
│    ├─ OS name & processor                   │
│    └─ C++ standard version                  │
│                                              │
│  Output: SHA-256(concatenated inputs)        │
│                                              │
│  Verification: Reject if mismatch            │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

This means that even the **same binary on the same platform** must have been built under the **exact same build environment** to execute. This is not an inconvenience — it is a **reproducible build guarantee**.

