## 4. Enterprise-Grade Security Architecture

### Multi-Layer Authorization Model

TortureLang implements a **four-layer** authorization model:

```
Layer 1: File-Level
  ├─ require ecc;  (mandatory elliptic curve cryptography declaration)

Layer 2: Function-Level
  ├─ code size N           (declare your code budget)
  ├─ max stack size N      (declare your stack budget)
  ├─ requires security level N  (minimum clearance)
  ├─ allowed roles admin, viewer  (role restrictions)
  └─ authorized by root    (declaration authority)

Layer 3: Operation-Level
  ├─ authorize use operator ==  (comparison operator license)
  ├─ authorize invocation of ...  (function call permission)
  └─ with io operation because literal "..."  (I/O declaration)

Layer 4: Approval-Level
  ├─ with approval of alwaysapprove  (approval function)
  ├─ with approval justification "..."  (written rationale)
  └─ with approval timeout N  (decision deadline)
```

Every authorization has an associated `because literal "..."` clause that **mandates a written justification**. This creates a complete **audit trail** for every operation in the codebase.

### Built-In Approval Functions

| Function | Behavior | Use Case |
|----------|----------|----------|
| `alwaysapprove` | Approves unconditionally | Trusted operations |
| `alwaysdeny` | Rejects unconditionally | Security testing |

Additional approval functions can be implemented to support:
- Multi-signature approval
- Time-locked approval
- Threshold-based approval
- Circuit-breaker patterns

### The `proceed verifyfunctionidentity()` Mandate

Every function body **must** begin with:

```torture
proceed verifyfunctionidentity();
```

This ensures that:
1. The function identity has been cryptographically verified before any code executes
2. No function can execute without first acknowledging its own identity
3. The runtime has an authenticated execution boundary at every entry point

