## 5. The Type System: Precision by Design

### Explicit Bit-Width Types

TortureLang requires **explicit bit-width annotations** on all types. No implicit type erasure. No silent integer widening.

| Type | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `int:8` | 8-bit signed integer |
| `int:16` | 16-bit signed integer |
| `int:32` | 32-bit signed integer |
| `int:64` | 64-bit signed integer |
| `uint:8` | 8-bit unsigned integer |
| `uint:16` | 16-bit unsigned integer |
| `uint:32` | 32-bit unsigned integer |
| `uint:64` | 64-bit unsigned integer |
| `float:32` | 32-bit IEEE 754 floating point |
| `float:64` | 64-bit IEEE 754 floating point |
| `char:8` | ASCII character |
| `char:32` | Unicode code point |
| `bool:1` | Boolean value |
| `chain` | Authority chain reference |
| `ptr` | Pointer (typed) |
| `ref` | Reference (typed) |
| `fptr` | Function pointer |

### Comparison Rules

TortureLang enforces **strict type-width equality** for comparisons:

```
int:32 == int:32  ✓  permitted
int:32 == int:64  ✗  rejected — width mismatch
int:32 == uint:32 ✓  permitted (signedness ignored for comparison)
char:8 == char:8  ✓  permitted
char:8 == char:32 ✗  rejected — width and semantics differ
bool:1 == bool:1  ✓  permitted (== and != only)
bool:1 < bool:1   ✗  rejected — boolean ordering not defined
```

This protects developers from a class of comparison-related defects that plague dynamically-typed and weakly-typed languages.

