## 7. The Invocation Framework: Every Call is a Contract

Function calls in TortureLang are not mere transfers of control — they are **legally binding contracts** between caller and callee.

### Full Invocation Syntax

```torture
authorize invocation of outputint
    at security level 1
    with memory limit 128
    with timeout 1000
    with io operation because literal "justification for I/O"
    with justification "operation description"
    with arguments { value by value = score }
    discarding return
    predictstackdepth 4
    with authority chain admin
    with approval of alwaysapprove
    with approval justification "approval rationale"
    with approval timeout 1000;
```

### What Each Clause Guarantees

| Clause | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `at security level N` | Declares the security clearance required |
| `with memory limit N` | Caps memory allocation for this call |
| `with timeout N` | Prevents runaway execution |
| `with io operation` | Acknowledges potential I/O side effects |
| `with justification` | Documents the purpose of the call |
| `with arguments { ... }` | Explicitly maps parameters |
| `discarding return` | Consciously ignores return value |
| `predictstackdepth N` | Declares expected stack usage |
| `with authority chain` | Identifies the delegation path |
| `with approval of` | Designates the approval authority |
| `with approval justification` | States why approval is granted |
| `with approval timeout` | Limits approval validity period |

